+ ##990011|2004##
++ 10 September
[[span style="font-family: BauhausLTDemi; font-size: 120%;"]]**[http://www.scpwiki.com/secure-facility-dossier-site-43 Site-43]: Lambton County, Ontario, Canada**[[/span]]
[[/=]]

----

It could have been worse.

They'd done well to start the debriefings as soon as the dust cleared. If they hadn't done that, they'd have been left with only whatever information was contained in Harry's florid history of the alternate timeline, and the contents of his electronic sketchbook — without which the entire year would have passed out of all knowledge without a trace. Even their clothes had disappeared; Sokolsky's examination had revealed nothing peculiar until half past six on the tenth, and then nothing at all. The PDAs had vanished as well. Ngo's notes and the transferred files appeared to be permanent, but there was no knowing how long that would last. They'd already been passed along to the Site-17 Deepwell.

The idea that his amateurish drawings had been immortalized, preserved as though they were among the foundational records of humankind, made Harry feel very, very silly. He wasn't opposed to being a part of history rather than writing it, but not like this. Not like //this.//

Someone was knocking on his door.

"Come on in."

The door opened, and Lillian entered tentatively. Harry frowned. He couldn't remember the last time she'd knocked before entering, or the last time she'd done anything tentatively. "What's up?"

"I've got a problem." She approached the couch where he was sitting like she was sneaking up on a tiger. He had no idea why. Instinctively, he stood up. "A new one?"

"A very new one," she nodded. "It's my memory."

"Okay."

"It's still there."

He nodded. "Okay... wait. It's still there?"

"All of it."

"You remember the entire year?"

"Pretty sure I do, guy." Was that a haunted look in her eye, or something else?

"What the fuck?"

"I don't know!"

"What are you gonna do?"

"I don't know!"

He paced the seating area, thinking it through. "Well, you have to tell McInnis. You'll probably have to debrief Ngo. Everything you remember could be important."

"Yeah." She massaged the back of her neck. "Fuck."

"What did you think I was gonna tell you?"

"I dunno." She shrugged. "We've gotten in the habit of keeping secrets."

"Did you tell anyone else?"

"Why would I have?"

There was an odd vulnerability in the way she said that flattering thing, and he felt a warm wave of affection for his oldest, best friend. "Can I tell you something?"

"Always."

He walked up to her, smiled up at her. "I'm glad we're suffering this horseshit together."

She bumped her forehead into his, and reached out to take his hands. "Nobody I'd rather get dumped on with."

They stood like that for a while. Her hands were shaking, and he wondered why. Before he could ask, she pulled him into an embrace, squeezed the breath out of him, then let go and stepped back. She'd seemed badly out of sorts when she'd walked through the door, but suddenly it all seemed better.

//Your mind is a strange and wondrous thing, Dr. Lillihammer,// he thought, and then he thought something else.

It must have made it out of his mind and onto his face, because Lillian frowned at him. "What?"

"I just had a thought."

"Thought I heard a rattling noise."

He grunted. The thought was too troubling for him to really enjoy the ribbing. "Do you know why..."

She waited a few seconds for him to continue -- something else she rarely ever did -- then finally ventured "Maybe?" when he didn't.

He remembered his last moments with Melissa, the one he'd lost less permanently, the one who was presently doing who knew what in Grand Bend, and hesitated. "I dunno if I should ask."

"Can it wait? Because you're right, I should tell the others about this."

"I dunno if I //want// it to wait." He sighed. "Okay. All right. Do you know why Udo and I broke up?"

Her eyes narrowed. "Yes."

He nodded.

She tilted her chin down. "Do you want me to tell you?"

"I... don't think so."

"Good, because I wasn't gonna."

Having already asked her something he shouldn't have, he decided to overshare as well. "We might get together again. Stay together, I mean."

She shrugged. "So?"

"So, is there a good reason why we shouldn't? Is there a mistake we need to avoid? You know how it plays out."

She smiled sadly. "I have no idea how it'll play out."

"Why?"

"Because that was then, and this is now."

