++ 11 September
[[/=]]

----

Representatives had arrived from two different groups claiming to represent the Foundation's time cops, the Department of Temporal Anomalies (which some of them had heard of) and the Temporal Anomalies Department (which only Udo Okorie and Ilse Reynders had heard of). A third representative from a third group nobody had heard of, a woman named Azzopardi who claimed to work for something called the Chronometrics Division, didn't stay long. She had credentials which didn't scan, produced a loud "eep" sound when she saw the TAD's rep and backed away from him, and repeated "2004? As in two //zero// zero four?" twice before making her apologies and her exit in quick succession.

The two who remained did a rapid readover of the personnel roster, then settled on meeting with Reynders and Xinyi Du. Okorie wasn't offended, since she hadn't offered up the fact that she'd heard of the TAD. She had the feeling that was the kind of thing that got you amnesticized, and the discovery was long enough ago now that she'd be losing rather a lot of herself in that case.

Then again, she thought, forgetting everything after 2002 was a fairly even mixture of good and bad.

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

"So." Alice Forth of the DTA was a round-faced brunette with bright green eyes and a tidy, bespoke business suit. She had a relatively easy manner, and a friendly smile. "You don't have any temporal affairs personnel."

"Of either acronym order, no," Du agreed.

"This is our first temporal affair," Reynders said without a hint of humour.

"Yes," Du agreed. "Please be gentle."

Forth smirked.

Thaddeus Xyank of the TAD was unamused. He looked like a shipping magnate from the 1920s, a huge handlebar moustache driving a badly out-of-date velvet suit. Personality wise, he was the perfect foil to Forth. "We chose to debrief the two of you because frankly, nobody else around here stands the slightest chance of grasping the temporal mechanics. I suspect you might be able to glean a glimmer, with intensive study."

Forth gave him a sidelong glance. "It's an honour to meet you, Dr. Reynders. Your work is foundational in the field."

Xyank checked the watch on his left hand, and sighed.

"The stuff I know I've done," Reynders asked, "or the stuff I'll do later?"

Both of them laughed. It seemed oddly forced from Xyank.

"We won't waste your time with the basics," said Forth. Xyank raised a bushy eyebrow at her, but did not protest. "Temporal alteration, timeline tangent."

"Unusual example, though," her counterpart mused. "Typically someone travels back in time, time doesn't travel forwards, then take what you did to it back //with// it."

"Yes," Forth agreed, "that's a wrinkle to be sure. But the basic principles seem the same. In a sense this arrangement is better than what you'd normally get; normally you'd have to contrive a means of returning to the scene of the time crime to set it right, but in this case--"

"The time-mountain comes to time-Mohammad," Du finished.

Xyank looked at him, then looked at Forth. "What makes people here talk like that?"

"Honestly?" Du shrugged. "It's mostly Lillihammer."

Forth nodded. "We were hoping to speak to her as well, actually, but I understand she's on another consult."

Reynders decided to essay a restart. "So, I don't know if you two have an agenda—"

"Why would I have an agenda?" Xyank snapped.

Forth gave him a strange look. "She means a plan for this meeting."

"Right. Of course. Uh, no." He checked the watch on his right hand this time. "When Dr. Forth and I end up in the same meeting, we usually end up arguing, and arguments are so much more productive unscripted."

"I disagree," Forth smiled.

"You two make a good light comedy act." Reynders tapped her pencil lightly on the window sill. "If you don't have an outline, let me express my main concern: how do we know that we're actually in baseline now? If it's so dependent on precisely what these people do, couldn't subtle differences in their actions have resulted in subtly different versions of September 8? Wettle fell over a second too late, and there's repercussions we might not even notice? I know that's not how it works most of the time, but as you said, none of this is standard."

The two visiting experts exchanged a meaningful glance.

"That's rather the crux of the matter, isn't it?" Xyank said. "Even if restoration to baseline is as forgiving as it ought to be, these seven individuals and their actions now directly define the survival of this entire timeline."

Forth continued this line of thought, to Xyank's very obvious distaste. He kept correcting her word choice with his lips as he listened. "If they do anything wrong, anything at all, it erases everything and rewrites the universe in the image of those... //individuals,// whoever they were. This facility is now the temporal anomalies equivalent of a superfund site."

"And how do you propose we clean it up?" Du asked.

"Foul the waters further," Xyank suggested. "Depart from the correct course minutely each year, and chart the effects until you understand the larger pattern."

Forth favoured him with a wide-eyed stare. "I would have said definitely do //not// do that. Make absolutely certain they do their jobs precisely the same way, year after year, until we can figure out what's causing this and devise a means of stopping it."

"What an unshockingly provincial outlook you have, Dr. Forth," Xyank sighed. "Do you know, every version of you I've met thinks much the same?"

"Do you know, Dr. Xyank," she retorted, "that Dr. McInnis told me you told him reality would rubberband back instantly on the 8th, or not at all?"

From his stricken expression, he had not in fact known that. "Yes, well, this is all rather new ground for all of us." He didn't look happy to be making that admission. "I'm also unaware of any temporal anomaly which restructures reality in stages, yet that's precisely what this one did."

Reynders rubbed her temples. "Yes, do you know, that gave me quite the headache? For an instant I was seeing triple: baseline, baseline but the Victims never died, baseline but the Victims never died and they were destroying the world." She reached out to touch her window, examining a specific and wholly unremarkable corner of the glass with inexplicable interest before catching herself and resuming the dialogue. "How do we even begin to figure out that sort of absurdity?"

Xyank twirled his moustache, but Forth beat him to the punch. "We're experts in absurdity. Just look at us." She simpered. "Mostly him, of course."

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

[[div class="muddle"]]
Site-43, it has often been remarked, violently breaks the mould when it comes to the physical appearance of its experts. They are typically younger, healthier, and while the final metric is wholly subjective, generally agreed to be more attractive than their colleagues elsewhere. This writer once suggested, to general expressions of disdain, that this might be due in large part to the large number of humanities PhDs on staff. He reasoned that the hard sciences attract fewer of the sensitive, artsy sorts who flock to fields like history, occultism or even memetics. "Makes you wonder why they call them 'hard'," he'd added to immediate and negative physical consequences.

[[>]]
-- Blank, //Lines in a Muddle//
[[/>]]
[[/div]]

With all that said, even by local standards Dr. Jessie Rivera did not seem like a world-renowned expert in anything, except perhaps for surfing or the growth and care of marijuana plants. She was a bouncy, freckled redhead in a floral tank top that looked like it belonged on a beach, in the 1990s. She was also apparently one of the Directors of Site-120, which apparently had more than one of those.  

"So yes," she was saying, "obviously it's ontokinetic. It can't not be. Reality got bent."

"Lucky reality," Udo smiled. They were walking to the subway, which gave Udo an uneasy feeling that she couldn't put her finger on.

Rivera laughed. "Right? Now, whatever happened to your unknown subject -- do you have a name for them? One that doesn't give you blackbox on the brain?"

"We've managed to find a few scraps referring to 'The Uncontained', contextually likely to be the occupant of that cell."

"Okay, so, your uncle. Whatever happened to him... oof, that hurt, got too close apparently." She blinked away the antimemetic blues. "Whatever happened to //them// isn't related to anything chronological. The erasure, I mean. If it was, the erasure would have been tidy. They wouldn't exist, instead of sort of kind of mostly not existing but also we've got lots of papers with nicknames for them on them."

The valley girl routine was making Udo's curiosity itch, and she finally relented. "How old are you?"

Rivera seemed momentarily surprised, then snorted. "Older than this." She gestured at her lithe, fit form. "Older than you. Probably older than your parents too."

"Why do you look so young?"

"Because I'm a reality bender."

"Ohhhhh." Udo chuckled. "So that's the difference between an 'expert in ontokinetics' and an 'ontokinetics expert'."

Rivera grinned. "Exactly!"

"How long have they known?"

"The Foundation? All along."

"Wow." She wasn't at all sure how she felt about that.

They headed into the H&P station without trading another word. The platform was empty, and they wouldn't have long to wait.

"Well, go ahead," Rivera said apropos of nothing.

Udo started. "Huh?" She realized she'd been staring, and thanked her genetics that she didn't blush very visibly.

"Ask me why I bother."

"I mean, it's pretty self-evident." Udo gestured, noting with no small amount of embarrassment that her hands trembled as she did it. "Who wouldn't want to look like that?" The other woman winked playfully at her, and Udo suspected even her dark skin was now flushing at least a little. "Is it your actual appearance?"

"Yup."

"I wouldn't wanna age either."

Rivera gave her an appraising look as the train pulled into the station. "If? If you looked like this, you mean? I think maybe you need a mirror."

The act of boarding the nearest car saved Udo from having to respond to that. She had no idea what she would have said.

"Anyway." Rivera sat down, and Udo sat down across the aisle from her. "It's my self-image. This is who I see when I picture myself. It's who I still feel like. So why would I change it?"

Udo nodded. The train left the station.

Rivera took her silence as an invitation to continue. "I once heard about a guy who didn't know he was a reality bender until he suddenly realized his mind was dressing him in his old clothes, and turning his grey hair back to red."

"I cut my hair in the alternate timeline," Udo volunteered. She only knew this because Ngo had used video recording apparatus for their debriefing.

"And now it's long again," Rivera noted. That Udo's hair was long was the first thing people generally noticed about her. Udo had orange eyes; that was how long her hair was.

"Yeah."

"Sounds like you and the other you don't share a self-image," the ontokineticist remarked.

"Apparently not." Udo examined her fingernails. "Alternate me also dumped my boyfriend, and I... don't want to."

Rivera shrugged. "So don't."

"That easy?"

"Oh, sure. We see this all the time. Other realities make us into other people. That doesn't make who you are right now any less valid. You want your hair short? Cut it again. You want to stick with your guy? Stick with him. Be the best version of yourself for living in your present circumstances. That's probably what alternate you did."

"I know some of my reasons, for some of the things we did. Well, you heard the debriefing."

"Too bad it wasn't in-depth. You ought to get some ontokinetics people working here full time. Forth and Xyank are probably selling your boss on the virtues of scheduled Temporal Anomalies consults, but guess what? Working to their schema, that twenty four hour grace period then wham!" -- she slammed her fist into her palm -- "would have come right out of left field. Their shit doesn't work like that, and they never would have predicted it for you. If I'd been in that room, I wouldn't have let any of you leave until the whole tale was told. Reality bending doesn't follow the rules. That's what distinguishes it from magic."

Udo refrained from offering to show Rivera how flexible her own magic was. Given her earlier open ogling, it might have come across as flirtatious, and the other woman was prominently displaying a wedding ring. "So you think this is more ontokinetic than temporal?"

"I think it's both, equally, which makes it an awful bitch of a mess. Hard to predict. There's definitely intentionality in there, though. The containment quality decline, by percentage points. The day-long grace periods. The arbitrary selections."

"Arbitrary selections?"

"You seven, with your unique relationships to the effects."

"We were the ones who most directly affected the course of the breach," Udo explained.

"That's neat. Why would an unthinking natural force know to single you out for that? And anyway, if I recall correctly, you //don't// recall doing anything of particular importance."

Udo's mouth migrated to one side of her face. "I closed a valve. That's not nothing."

"Unless the valve was in your head," Rivera smirked, "it doesn't explain why it preserves your memories between realities."

"Yeah. It's a mystery, alright."

"Well, we'll see what we can figure out for you today. There's a guy I want to talk to about this."

"Somebody special?"

"Oh, yes. Very special."

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

[[div class="muddle"]]
There is a room in Acroamatic Abatement Facility AAF-A which only Level 4+ personnel are cleared to enter, and then only with permission from the Chief of Identity and Technocryptography, the Site Director, or the O5 Council. It contains nothing more sophisticated than a single computer terminal.

It is perhaps the single most important piece of containment equipment at Site-43.

[[>]]
-- Blank, //Lines in a Muddle//
[[/>]]
[[/div]]

Rivera sat down at the terminal. Udo stood behind her; behind her, leaning on the wall and scrolling idly through her tablet, Eileen Veiksaar seemed almost bored.

Rivera cracked her knuckles, and began to type.

[[div class="danke site"]]
Can you feel me?
[[/div]]

The response came almost instantly.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Who are you, young lady?
[[/div]]

"It's because I'm a reality bender," Rivera explained. "He's got a keen sense for that, and he's able to sense things he shouldn't be able to from all the way down there. As you can see, he's very powerful."

Udo felt a sudden desire to graduate from exposition sink to expositor in her own right. "He teleported me up here once."

Rivera turned to look at her, surprise clouding her freckled face. "What? That wasn't in the debriefing."

Udo smiled. "I'll get you a copy of Harry's alt history book before you go back to 120."

Rivera returned to her keyboard.

[[div class="danke site"]]
Think of me as a colleague.
[[/div]]

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Have you come to join the work?
[[/div]]

[[div class="danke site"]]
What work is that?
[[/div]]

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
The only work. 
[[/div]]

"They always get myopic," Rivera mused. "Reality benders. It's an occupational hazard. They end up stuck inside their own little worlds where nothing else seems to matter."

"How do you get them out again?" Udo asked.

"If they're weak enough, an SRA will do the trick."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
If they're too powerful, though, or it's been too long, they have to want to come back.
[[/div]]

"Uh," said Udo.

Rivera backed her chair away from the screen a little. "//That// was spooky."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
I've never met anyone quite like you, Dr. Rivera. Well, except for me. I've met myself a few times. Nice fellow. A little erratic, but he means well.
[[/div]]

"I'm given to understand you've met Dr. Lillihammer before." Their eyes met, all three pairs. Veiksaar was very interested now; Udo had a feeling Rydderech didn't often allow his visitors to skip the part where they tapped out their half of the conversation.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Always a fine young woman. Very clever. And red hair! Not very Finnish. I suspect there's a little Welsh in her makeup.
[[/div]]

"Can't remember him ever being this coherent before," Veiksaar murmured. Udo had the feeling she was saying it quietly in the hopes that he wouldn't hear.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
It is a good day in hell today, interlocutor mine.
[[/div]]

"Do you remember giving her some advice?" Rivera asked the air. "Dr. Lillihammer, I mean?"

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Are you trying to read ahead?
[[/div]]

"What?"

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
That's naughty. And pointless. You want all the revelations at once? They won't mean anything to you -- by which I mean you won't understand them, and you'll take them for granted. Better to let the story unfold chapter by chapter than rush right through.
[[/div]]

Rivera rolled her eyes, and mouthed //yeah// at them. The unspoken remainder of the sentence was probably something like //they get like this sometimes too.// "I'm not asking you to tell me what you told her. I just want to know if you can tell me why you exist in more than one timeline simultaneously, and also //how.//"

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
There is only one timeline.
[[/div]]

"We know that isn't true."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Isn't it? Maybe I'm the one reading ahead.
[[/div]]

Rivera sighed. "Dr. Rydderech, these... let's call them reality shifts. You can tell they're happening."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Yes, I feel it in my trick knee.
[[/div]]

"I know chronometrics weren't understood in your era, but--"

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
It's still my era.
[[/div]]

"Well, of course."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
I'm still at work down here.
[[/div]]

"Of course you are."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
And I don't need to know chronometrics to answer your question. But if I did, I'd invent them.
[[/div]]

"Well," Rivera chuckled. "Dr. Reynders already invented them."

Was it Udo's imagination, or did the terminal whine at a higher pitch when it printed the next word?

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Ilse?
[[/div]]

"That's right," Rivera nodded. Udo hoped the nod was just a reflex action, that it didn't mean the ontokineticist thought Rydderech was actually watching their body language now. Even at Site-43, where everyone was under surveillance twenty four hours per day, the sensation of being watched was never particularly present.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Will you tell her something for me?
[[/div]]

"If you answer my question, sure."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Time is progressive. Your problem is retrogression. It doesn't make sense in your models because it isn't the same thing.

[[/div]]

"Well," Rivera's head tilted from side to side as she considered how to rebut him, "but it basically //is.// It's still a matter of temporal mechanics."

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
It's a matter of course, not a matter of time.
[[/div]]

She frowned. They all frowned. "What does that mean?" Rivera demanded.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
I'm sorry, vertometrics weren't invented in your era.
[[/div]]

Udo didn't know what that meant, but she did know to laugh.

"I think he's lost the plot again," Rivera sighed.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Oh! Well said. Perhaps I was wrong.
[[/div]]

"Is there anything more you can tell us?" Udo asked. Veiksaar raised an eyebrow at her, and she mouthed //sorry// in response. She wasn't even a doctor yet, no matter how often everyone called her one. She certainly wasn't cleared to be talking with the Site's biggest secret, even if he had rearranged her atoms once.

//__God__ I hope he's the Site's biggest secret.//

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
It's good to see you made it up there alright. You won't next time.
[[/div]]

She felt suddenly faint. "What?"

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Could you put Vivian back on, please?
[[/div]]

Rivera rubbed her temples. "We need to wrap this up."

"Why?" Udo asked. "Are you feeling alright?"

"Not really?" The other woman shivered. "It's taking a lot out of me. I think he's drawing on the potential energy in this room to stay lucid, and I'm starting to run dry."

"Well," Udo said, "fair's fair. Dr. Rydderech, what did you want us to tell Dr. Reynders?"

There was a pause. For a moment, Udo expected the terminal to print something like {{Who is Dr. Reynders?}}

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Tell her that it's very bad form to be in two places at once, but one place at twice is bad //taste.//
[[/div]]

//What.// She saw the same primordial question written on each of their faces.

[[div class="danke wynn"]]
Vivian? Don't go with them. I can't protect you there, because I didn't.
[[/div]]

