Rivera kept her eyes closed on the subway ride back, clearly exhausted.

She didn't seem to mind Udo's questions, however. "Was it him? Dr. Rydderech? Was he the man in your story with the changing clothing and hair?"

"That's right."

"You used a Level 5 anomaly as an //anecdote?//"

"He became accustomed to who he was, and kept his identity static. Stable."

"Static, yes. Stable, well." Udo reached out to hold the vertical bar in front of her. She was sitting down, but after their shared experience even the smooth curves of the Blue Line threatened to send her pitching forward. "You saw."

Rivera opened her eyes. "What if that's what's happening with September 8?"

"Go on."

"What if the breach killed a reality bender, infused all the materials flying about in there with its essence, and the bender became the breach? That's why its effects work according to a human sort of illogic. The breach is //sapient.//"

Udo should have been floored by the suggestion, but instead she felt energized. "I'll do you one better."

"Okay." Rivera's eyes closed again. She was breathing very shallowly.

"The materials you're talking about, a lot of them were chronological and counter-chronological."

This time the eyes snapped open, and focused on her face with laser intensity. "Oh, hell."

"Right?"

"What if September 8 is sapient?"

Udo laughed. "Right. But obviously that's insane."

"Think about it, though." Rivera leaned forward wobbily. "Self-image. Those six minutes have a mind of their own, a personality, but they're receptive to change. We make alterations to its circumstances, and it changes itself to follow."

Udo shook her head. "I don't think we need to personalize the disaster to make that work."

"I do. Because that explains why it singled you out. It identified you as its influences, and it wants you to judge the results."

"That's--" She couldn't finish the sentence. She didn't know what it was.

"Take it a step further. Maybe it wants you to figure out how to free it from the breach."

Udo ran her tongue across the front of her teeth. "What if it sees us as its opponents, for making the breach end?"

Rivera sagged back in her chair, and closed her eyes for the last time. "Alternatively, what if it's just an explosion?"

She slept for the remainder of the short ride back.

