Lillian had been expecting the knock, but she'd allowed herself to lapse back into what she was now calling Memory Mode, reviewing the events of the alternate timeline for any further clues to their overall dilemma, so she was still a little startled when it came. "Come in!"

A short young woman in a nice suit with electric blue square-rimmed glasses and a complex weave of curly black hair walked in, and shut the door behind her. She'd made it past the memetic decontamination tunnel with no obvious ill effects. "Dr. Lillihammer. Do you r--"

Lillian kicked off her desk, and snatched up her tablet. "Who the fuck are you? Don't move. I'm calling security!"

The other woman raised her hands in a placating gesture, then slowly moved one of them to her suit pocket. "Wait! I have ID."

Lillian laughed at her. "Just fucking with you. Been a long time, Marion."

The agent's face returned to its standard neutral-trending-to-disapproval configuration. "You're not funny."

"I'm not as funny as I think I am, that's for sure." Lillian gestured. "Sit down."

Marion Wheeler took the seat, brushing the hem of her suit jacket aside to reveal a concealed holster. "You do know I carry a gun?"

"Which means you're trusted not to shoot panicky researchers." Lillian kicked her feet up on the table. "Did you really think I'd forgotten you?"

"I really did." It took a lot to get Wheeler's pulse going, but Lillian's dangerous joke had done the job. The otherwise unflappable woman was flushed with adrenaline.

"Well, I wouldn't worry. You're unforgettable. You're tied into a core memory, from real early in my career. Before we met. Besides which, I never forget anything."

"This I am aware of. So, for example--"

"You think you get to move on to examples before explanations? Not in my broom closet. What's this visit about?"

Wheeler's eyes opened a little wider, as did her mouth, in the universal gesture for //sure, alright, let's do this then.// "You people tripped our sensors half a dozen times in two years. If it hadn't been for the lack of manpower, I'd have come a lot sooner."

"That sentence was like a gift basket addressed to me."

"Thanks for not unwrapping it. My point is, this place is lousy with antimemetic activity. First you lost a hostile GoI's attention for no explicable reason; then you lost six minutes of a registered thaumaturge's time during a cascade containment breach; then you lost an apparently vital SCP object, so vital it had its own secret sublevel, now blackboxed out of reality; //then// you //found// a network of self-erasing spies at Area-21; then you found them //again// at Site-43 in an alternate timeline, then //forgot the alternate timeline itself.// Is that all, or did //I// forget anything?"

"There's a thing re: forgetting you don't know about yet, but I'll remember to bring it up if it gets relevant. But yeah. When you say all that at once, it does sound bad. What did you mean about the thing where I could have made a sex joke? Manpower?"

"We're understaffed and underfunded." She said it the way Lillian might have talked about a persistent shoulder ache, something unpleasant she'd long become accustomed to.

"My old supervisor told me you guys have a low life expectancy."

"Could be," Wheeler nodded. "Could be we used to have the numbers we need, and they all walked into invisible mouths and down invisible gullets and got invisibly digested. Could also be that they just stopped being visible to the rest of us. Could even be a more mundane reason. But antimemetic research isn't a popular field besides that, for obvious reasons. Everyone likes to forget the bad things, but forgetting the good is terrifying."

"Can't relate. Anyhow, to what //in specific// do I owe the pleasure of an Antimemetics Division consult?"

There were much-maligned departments at the SCP Foundation. Just about nobody who didn't work there was fond of Pataphysics. Surrealistics, Semiotics, and Miscommunications were always major headaches to deal with. Even Tactical Theology offended the sensibilities of some of Lillian's less whimsical colleagues, usually the ones who'd been staunch atheists before the unpleasant discovery that gods did, in fact, exist, and didn't much care for being persistently reminded they'd been wrong. But the Antimemetics Division was truly beyond the pale. It wasn't that people dreaded their coming, it was more that they were almost always unexpected. The average researcher had trouble even remembering they existed. Anyone dealing with them regularly had to take special drugs to avoid forgetting that any such group had ever been formed. It was probably a red letter day for Marion, getting to consult with someone who didn't have to first be debriefed on what her entire deal was — the investigation of things which could not be perceived and stored in the little grey cells without tremendous effort and very often not even then, the invisible world which, having no sense of fair play, was often watching every move made in the visible one. Monsters that fed on recollection. Immemorial predators. Thoughts that couldn't be contained in the human mind, the noospheric equivalent of recondite particles. Lillian had once been considered as a potential recruit for the Division, and Wheeler had been her assessing officer.

The rejection remained one of the highest compliments she'd ever been paid.

The other woman rolled her eyes. "Your debriefing from the alternate timeline made its way to my desk. At least someone at Temporal Anomalies, or Temporal Anomalies, is on the ball."

"What made this time so different?"

Wheeler frowned. "What do you mean?"

"I CC'd you guys on the //geistschreiber// when we first found out about them. Didn't hear shit back. Assumed you didn't care."

The frown deepened. Wheeler's composed expression was rarely more than one unpleasant revelation away from creasing up in frustration. "We never got that CC."

"You really need to work on your visibility. Have you tried taking out billboards?"

"They'd just end up killing birds. What can you tell me about the //geistschreiber// that isn't in the reports? I know you know what's in them."

//I never should have let them put 'eidetic memory' in my file.// "Alright, sure. We've only talked to one of them in a situation where they're unlikely to have been bullshitting at maximum PSI, and it was the same one in baseline and the alternate. Her name is Alis."

"Presently in custody at Site-06."

"Yeah. That. When our security chief interrogated her after she tried to blow us all up -- Alis, not the Chief -- she got a lot of bluster about the inevitable end of the world in the most obnoxious know it all supervillain tone you could imagine. That's not in the report, but you can see it in the transcript for yourself."

"Okay."

"She wasn't like that at 43. But the Victims were."

"The seven particularly problematic individuals."

"Or the six we actually saw, yeah. Five? We didn't actually see Wirth... anyhow. They talked the same way. The //exact// same way. It was more than just an organization thing. It was more like a personality tic."

The frustration had shifted toward boredom. Wheeler got bored very easily when things weren't up her alley. Lillian respected that about her. "Hmm."

"Not really your area, right?"

"Not really," the other woman agreed. "You've got people for parapsychology. I'm here for more forgettable things."

A thought occurred. "Well, actually... hmm."

"What?"

"Can you keep a secret?"

Wheeler arched an eyebrow.

"Sorry, low blow. Alright. This isn't in any report, and it can't be in yours either. Those are my terms. I'm only telling you this in the first place because we have history."

"Will not reporting it put anyone in danger?"

"Nope."

"Then fine." Wheeler adjusted her glasses. "Tell me your big secret."

"We all forgot the alternate timeline the day after coming back from it."

"That's in the addendum to the file," the antimemeticist sighed. "I read it on the flight over."

"Cool. So obviously that's your outfit's kinda thing, but try this on for size on top of it: //I// did not forget. I still haven't."

Both eyebrows this time. "Really."

"Really. I remember everything."

"Your memories didn't sync to baseline like the others?"

"They synced, but were not replaced. I know both versions."

Wheeler's mouth formed into an 'o'. "//That// is //very// strange."

"Right?"

"Do you have an explanation?"

"I'm special."

"Do you have a useful explanation?"

"I'm useful. I've got the best memory at Site-43. I'm trained in countermemetics. I can look at kill agents without getting killed. Maybe I'm too spicy to sync."

Wheeler wasn't buying it. She was a savvy customer. "Have you tried asking our captive ghostwriter about it?"

Lillian wasn't capable of forgetting things, but like anyone else she couldn't focus on everything she knew at the same time. Unlike everyone else, she could focus on a great deal at once, but Alis Rydderech in her padded cell hadn't nearly made the cut. "Now, there's a thought. No. I haven't."

Wheeler stood. "Thanks for your time."

Lillian stood as well. "I'm coming with you."

The other woman shook her head, then had to perform emergency surgery on her wild crop of curls. "I'm heading back to Site-41."

"I'm not coming with you //now,// then, but we both know you're going to interview Alis soon. Let's kill two birds with one stone."

"What if we're the--"

"What if we're the birds and she's the stone, yeah, the math works out that way, doesn't it?" Lillian shrugged. "Well, unless you've slowed down a lot in three years, I think we can still fly circles around her."

