++ 12 September
[[/=]]

----

"Friends." McInnis smiled at them each in turn, all six of them. "It's time we formalized our little arrangement."

"Yeah," Lillihammer agreed. "We should all get together in some official conspiracy thing. Oh, wait."

They were sitting in their //de facto// clubhouse, Okorie's quarters. Harry was at his accustomed position on the couch next to his on-again-off-again, and their body language suggested they weren't sure which state was which anymore. Everyone else was where they usually sat: Lillihammer in her chair, Ibanez and Nascimbeni at opposite ends of the dining table, McInnis at the wall, Wettle on the floor.

"I take it," Harry sighed, "you mean setting up proper protocols for September 8 next year."

"Please don't let this happen again next year," the old tech moaned.

"It's happened three times," Okorie reminded him needlessly. "We have to assume it's going to keep on happening."

"Meetings happen all the time," Wettle interjected. "It's not so bad. You don't even have to go."

Harry sank down in the cushions. "Willie..."

"I could invite Dr. Elstrom into this conversation," McInnis threatened, "if you are unable to govern yourselves."

They all sat up straighter, and looked at him silently.

"Thank you. Now, I am going to have to ask rather a lot from this little group in the coming years. Repeating the events of one of the worst days of your professional lives is no easy task for which to prepare. I therefore intend to recommend all of you, and myself, for a strict training regimen."

Harry's expression shifted from exhaustion to suspicion. "What sort of training?"

"Survival training."

The archivist's face fairly collapsed. "Oh, god."

"Kiss your paunch goodbye," Lillihammer crowed.

"//You// kiss it."

Okorie gave him a complicated look.

"Can I be excused with a doctor's note?" Wettle whined.

"What would even be the point of survival training?" Nascimbeni demanded. "We're not going to go to war with the bodies we build, we'll have to make do with the ones we get zapped into."

"Yeah," Harry pointed at him, "good point. Doesn't matter how svelte we get--"

"You will never be 'svelte'," Lillihammer laughed.

"--because we'll be leaving these bodies in baseline."

"Two counterarguments to that," McInnis responded. "First, survival training will increase your physical health. We don't know how long these breaches will keep up, and we can't afford to lose any of you while they're ongoing. In fact, I'm going to recommend that each of you be granted life extension healthcare of the sort typically reserved for Site Directors, to give us as much time to find a solution as possible."

"Wait." Nascimbeni's mouth hung open between words. "You're going to make us immortal?"

"You think this is going to take //decades?//" Okorie added. 

"Seriously." Ibanez looked disgusted.

McInnis wasn't surprised to see how they reacted. Okorie and Ibanez were the youngest, so they were more concerned with long commitment than the steady march of time. Nascimbeni was the oldest, and the prospect of arresting his progress must have seemed appealing. Harry had a foot in both camps, and neither Lillihammer nor Wettle appeared to be listening at all now. "//Second,//" he resumed, "learning bodily control will enable you to make the most of any physique you jump into when the timeline switches."

"Again," said Lillihammer, who could quip even when she was only barely following the conversational thread, "my guy here will never have anything that can be fairly described as a //physique.//"

"Shut up," Harry growled. "I don't like that we're assuming this is inevitably going to happen again."

"Oh my god," Ibanez started. "Anyone wanna say that for the forty-seventh time?"

Wettle opened his mouth.

Harry raised a hand. "I don't mean the breach, I mean fucking it up. It's defeatist to assume we'll end up creating another timeline."

"We //must// make that assumption," said McInnis.

"But the avoidance steps are so simple!" Okorie cried.

"Shit happens," Nascimbeni sighed.

McInnis nodded. "Precisely."

They all looked at Wettle.

"What? I don't have any questions, or anything."

"As I stated at the outset," McInnis continued, I wish to make formal arrangements for addressing this anomaly. To that end, I propose the following: creating a new SCP file covering the effects of the breach, and creating a Provisional Task Force to manage its containment."

"Super goddamn provisional," Ibanez grumbled. "One day per year."

"With significant preparatory duties, of course."

"Got a name in mind? Naming these things is half the reason to make them."

He spread his hands wide. "I am open to suggestions."

"The Survivors," Nascimbeni said immediately. Several of them nodded.

"We can continue using that term internally, but I suspect the other personnel of this facility might misunderstand the meaning."

Wettle blinked. "How?"

"If we're the Survivors," Harry told him, "it implies that everyone else //isn't.//"

"Big yikes," Wettle agreed.

"Timeline Travellers," Lillihammer suggested.

Okorie shifted excitedly on the couch. "Yeah!"

"Already taken," said McInnis.

The memeticist frowned. "By who?"

"They're from another timeline. It's complicated."

Okorie raised her hands dramatically. "Doom Patrol."

"Too dramatic."

"The Replacements," said Ibanez.

"Let's not make it too clear how this works, please."

Nascimbeni's delivery suggested he knew his next suggestion was far too tortuous, and didn't care. "Set Wrong What Once Went Wrong."

Harry laughed.

"Replication Students," said Wettle.

Harry leaned forward. "Heyyyy."

"That's pretty good," Lillihammer admitted begrudgingly.

At roughly the same time, Okorie said "I vote for that" and Nascimbeni said "Works for me."

"I can live with it," Ibanez yawned.

She was right to yawn. It was getting late, and there was much to organize on the coming day. "If there are no other suggestions..."

Harry stood up. "Good stuff. Now if you'll excuse me, I'm going to go have a mental breakdown for the next twelve months. See you in September."

"Fuck," said Lillihammer.

"Ah," said Nascimbeni.

"Shit," said Ibanez. "Yeah."

"Yeah," Okorie agreed.

Wettle looked from face to face, still flat-assed on the floor. "What?"

Harry was nodding to himself now. "That's the one, isn't it?"

"Gotta be." Lillihammer reached down to pat Wettle's head. "Sorry, Willie."

"What happened?"

McInnis rolled his sweater sleeves back down, and detached from the wall. "I'll file the paperwork."

Wettle stayed on the floor as the rest of them got up. "Did I miss something?"

