++ 19 September
[[span style="font-family: BauhausLTDemi; font-size: 120%;"]]**[http://www.scpwiki.com/secure-facility-dossier-site-169 Site-169]: Glassford Hill, Yavapai County, Arizona, United States of America**[[/span]]
[[/=]]

----

The first few days on the open-air track were murder, for most of them.

McInnis and Ibanez were in tip-top shape, though the latter bristled at the suggestion she should have to jog in plain sight. She tended to attract a crowd whenever she did that, and she wasn't in the mood for attracting; they were here for work, not play, despite the fact that 169 was the Foundation's only dedicated recreational facility. Lillihammer was lean and lithe, but she typically spent more time standing around than walking or running, so the daily track practice wiped her out in relatively short order. Okorie had never expended much effort on building her muscles, and they started aching fast when she put them to the test despite the super-science supplements they were all taking to boost their mass gain. For Blank, Wettle, and particularly Nascimbeni, the jogging was absolute torture.

"This feels like old man exercise," the old technician puffed.

"That's what you get for being an old man." The Director was keeping pace with him easily. He could have left him in the dust, if he'd wanted to.

"I'm still in my prime."

"Then let's see another lap."

"You're cheating." It was getting difficult to talk. "You're a //ringer.//"

"This is true." McInnis swung around and began jogging backward. He was still faster than Nascimbeni.

"How did swimming fit into your master plan to become communicator-in-chief?"

"Think about it. I talk to people all day long at my station."

"Right..."

"Then I go to the gym to work out."

"Okay..."

"And what do people do?"

Nascimbeni huffed, and immediately regretted the change in his breathing rhythm. It took him a moment to get back enough air to respond. "They talk to you."

McInnis turned back around, dancing on his heels to return to Nascimbeni's side. "But there's no talking in swimming. At least, there isn't meant to be."

"You make a good argument." Nascimbeni put his head down, and closed his eyes. He had to focus if he was going to get through this.

"And it's good for the cardiac health, as well."

"You've made your damn point," he grunted.

"Allow me to make another: if you're going to use this as an excuse not to talk, it needs to be because you're talking elsewhere."

"Like?"

"I think you know."

He let his superior eat indignant silence for a few seconds before replying. "I don't need advice on my social and family life, Allan."

"That would be a comfort and relief to believe."

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

"I can't take this anymore," Wettle panted.

"Move your fat ass!" Del shouted, hopping up and down beside the obstacle course in the centre of the track.

"//You// move it!" he cried, and ran gut-first into the next hurdle.

"Having fun yet?" Udo smiled from just ahead of Harry.

He kept his arms swinging and his legs pumping. He wanted to collapse, but he wasn't going to do it in front of -- or rather behind -- her. "I think I'm going to have a heart attack."

"So, you're //not// having fun."

He glanced down at her track pants, and decided to make that his motivation to continue. He made no move to catch up with her. "I'm gonna tell you a secret."

"I'm listening." She glanced over her back, following the his eyeline, and performed one of her not-quite-blushes when she figured it out.

"I hate exercise."

She raised an eyebrow. "All exercise?"

He raised her another. "You have something in mind?"

"I know a time-tested full body workout... but no, you wouldn't be interested in that." She turned to face down the track as they rounded the bend.

"No?"

"Wouldn't help at all with the whole heart attack thing," she explained.

"Well, I was more worried about it happening doing something I hate."

She nodded in mock contemplation. "So you're open to trying a new technique."

"That's what I'm saying." He should have been out of breath, but he was getting a not entirely inexplicable second wind now.

Lillian zoomed past them at a sprint. "Race you to the grave!"

"That's the spirit!" Del called from the obstacle course, where she was carefully untying Wettle's sweat pants from the rope climb.

