++ 9 October
[[span style="font-family: BauhausLTDemi; font-size: 120%;"]]**##990011|Site-06##: Outside Bad Karlshafen, Kassel District, Hesse, Federal Republic of Germany**[[/span]]
[[/=]]

----

Lillian had put a hold on visits to Alis Rydderech using the extra authority afforded her as member of a Clearance Level 5 Provisional Task Force, just in case Wheeler tried to make the visit without her while the strength and survival training was underway. After a few weeks at Site-169, and an extended camping trip in Baby Bone Wood near Sloth's Pit, Wisconsin which taught all of them except Ibanez how little they understood about esoteric prepperism, they were finally judged hale and hearty enough to get back to active duty for the time being. To soothe the antimemeticist's wounded pride, Lillian arranged for Epsilon-43 to fly them in to Site-06 direct.

The facility existed under the cover of a wildlife preserve. Their Sea King helicopter had to endure the application of a wrap proclaiming it to belong to the Federal Agency for Nature Conservation, and the two of them had to endure a brief photoshoot to produce their fake IDs in the unlikely event that their cover was blown. The chopper touched down on a helipad surrounded by trees in a dip in the earth, and the helipad promptly dipped down even further on greased rails. A bomb silo door closed over top of them, and as soon as the platform stopped moving, armed guards appeared everywhere.

"They don't fuck around with security, do they?" Lillian remarked as one of the facemasked grunts waved what looked like, and probably was not, a metal detector over her.

Site-06 was where the Foundation sent its most dangerous prisoners. Many of them had once been agents or researchers. Some of them had been, and probably still were, Insurgents. Serpents Hand thaumaturges. Particularly theatrical anartists. Reality benders.

And, since late April of 2003, two //geistschreiber.//

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

"Man," Lillian remarked as she sat down at the table.

"What," Alis murmured.

"I was gonna lead with 'why so blue', but you changed your hair. This your natural?"

Alis's hair was now the colour her eyebrows had been in both iterations, a deep burgundy. Her skin was sallower than it had been at Area-21, since she'd spent the intervening year and a half underground, and she had thicker bags beneath her eyes. She looked defeated, which was good, because she was.

She was not, however, in a cooperative mood. "How about I pull my jumpsuit down, and you can check on your way to kissing my ass?"

Wheeler sat down next to Lillian, and the agent who'd led them to the cell closed the door. Alis glanced at her, then back at Ibanez. "Who's this?"

"I'm here to ask you a few questions." Wheeler didn't carry a tablet, or a clipboard. She placed both hands on the table, and clasped them together.

Alis hunched forward. "Let me get my bearings first. Which of you is the cynic, and which one wants to believe?"

"I don't know what you're talking about." From the way Wheeler's lip curled, Lillian knew it wasn't true. "Do you know anything about alternate timelines?"

"Like, Harry Turtledove shit?" Alis shrugged. "Not my thing."

Wheeler gestured at Lillian. "My colleague here just spent a year in your company."

"And not the year you remember," Lillian added.

One of the //geistschreiber//'s eyebrows raised about a micrometer. "Were we the best of friends? Did I teach you all my deepest, darkest secrets?"

"You fucked Wettle again."

Alis recoiled, and slapped the table angrily. "God dammit. Shut up."

"Dr. Lillihammer is the only one who still remembers the events of the alternate timeline," Wheeler continued. "Everyone else's memories reverted. Any idea why that might be?"

"Nope." Alis was working her jaw, like she was trying to pop the joint. Maybe she was hoping to drown out the memory of sex with William Wettle via blinding pain. "Shouldn't work that way."

Wheeler nodded. "So you //do// know something."

"Oh, sure. I know all about alternate timelines. I'm from one."

The casual way she said this, Lillian almost missed it. Wheeler, however, came alive. "Do tell."

"My ancestors came here in a magic flying mansion, and when the world's about to end, I'll leave here in it. Isn't that great?" She snorted. "I think it's great."

Lillian sighed. "You've been in here how many months? You could have spent the time making up a better story."

"Who says I'm making anything up? I'm just so excited to have visitors, I'm spilling all the beans. A girl gets lonely, you know?"

Wheeler stood up. Lillian followed suit.

"Wait," the prisoner winced. "Please wait."

Wheeler waited. "I've got precisely zero time to waste on your smartass bullshit today."

"I'm sorry." She did look sorry. "Sit down."

They sat back down. "That might be the first thing you've said that wasn't soaked in irony," Lillian noted.

"I wasn't kidding. It's lonely in here." Alis placed both elbows on the table, and framed her tired face with both hands. "I'm in solitary, do you get that? Nobody's spoken more than a few words to me in three months."

"You know what?" Lillian smiled at her. "I'm going to say it anyway. Why so blue?"

"You're faking the arrogance this time around," Wheeler added. "It's not making it past your voice box. Are you depressed?"

Lillian clapped. "You don't believe in all your magic cult bullshit anymore, do you?"

"Pick that up from alternate me?" Alis frowned.

"Yeah, in point of fact."

"Just level with us," Wheeler suggested.

The //geistschreiber// looked back and forth between them, several very different emotions fighting for control over her face. "I don't trust you."

"Trust this." Lillian smiled nastily at her. "At your present level of cooperation, your only chance of getting out of here is a precisely targeted earthquake."

"I'm never getting out of here," Alis retorted, "no matter what I do. You haven't got any carrots to dangle."

"I'd have thought you'd at least take this opportunity to try and convert us to your cause," Wheeler remarked.

Alis shrugged. "What's the point?"

"Yes." Lillian nodded. "What //is// the point?"

"Okay. You know what?" Alis threw up her hands. "Fuck it. I don't care anymore. Here's the deal. I don't know why I did what I did."

"Yeah." Lillian smiled at her. "I know."

"You know what the //giftschreiber// are too, right?"

"Chaos meme cult. Disorganized. Violent. Insurgency with a better name, and a lot more creativity."

Alis paused. "I could tell you things about the Chaos Insurgency, if you want."

"This isn't about what she wants," Wheeler interrupted.

"We could make it--"

"This is about what I need as an agent of the Foundation's first line response against antimemetic threats. I need to know everything you know about the //giftschreiber.//"

"And you'll believe me?"

"No, but I'll treat what you say as potential data."

Alis smirked. "Good enough. So here's the thing, right? When I was with them, in the in-group, it all made sense. Then your sewage factory blew up, and we all lost the plot. //Then// you dumped me in here for a year, and now I honestly couldn't tell you a single thing they told me that I still believe."

"Sounds like memetic compulsion," Wheeler mused.

"Sounds more like one of those overlays we encountered," said Lillian.

Wheeler blinked. "Overlays?"

"Someone else's personality elements and personal drive overlaid on yours. You're still mostly you, but someone's nudging the tiller."

"That," Alis nodded vigorously. It was the first real vigour she'd displayed since they'd come in. "That's what it felt like with the //giftschreiber.// That exactly."

"So you drank the Kool Aid," Lillian said, "and it made you a good little soldier, but now it's wearing off."

"I guess."

"How does your antimemetic effect work?" Wheeler pressed.

"Indiscriminately. I can't turn it on or off. It's always on, and I have to be extra memorable to overcome it."

"You were wearing a low-yield meme coat in the alternate timeline," Lillian recalled. "Bright, like your hair. All the other memeticists ditched their dazzlewear early on, because none of them wanted to be extra visible with monsters prowling the place. You, on the other hand, had to light up and //present// just so people wouldn't forget that you were there."

The //geistschreiber// nodded. "Yep. Checks out."

"How did you acquire it?" Wheeler asked. "Your glamour?"

"You call this glamour?" Alis puffed out her D-class jacket.

Wheeler stared at her.

"You're not as fun as the 43 people. Well, I don't remember."

"Is that a joke?" Wheeler demanded.

"I wish it was. We were going to start inducting new members when you had your little disaster, and poof! totally forgot how it works."

Wheeler suddenly stood. "You'll have to excuse us for a moment."

"Can't very well refuse," Alis shrugged.

"Yeah." Lillian stood up as well. "Fun how this works, eh?"

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

Lillian started to speak the moment the door sealed behind them. The guard stepped away to give them privacy. "You're thinking what I'm thinking."

"I am," Wheeler agreed.

"And we didn't even have to be in the same memetic cult."

"The erasure of whatever was in the empty chambers on your secret fourth sublevel is what confused the //giftschreiber.//"

"And whatever it was, it gave them their power."

"A power source? An artifact? A //mentor?//"

"I'd lean towards the latter. That would explain--"

"The personality overlay."

"Yeah."

"So let's say you had some sort of next level cryptomancer down there, and they got aerosolized by the incident. Would that explain your seven crazy colleagues?"

"Assuming you mean the dead ones, yes."

"Would it explain why you still remember the alternate timeline?"

"No."

Wheeler took off her glasses, and rubbed her eyes. For someone so young, she had very old eyes. "I think we should try mnestic therapy on your friends, see if they can recall--"

The hall lights snapped to red.

"Uh oh," said Lillian.

The guard immediately walked back toward them, weapon raised. "Ma'ams, I need you to--"

Wheeler shot him in the chest. He dropped like a sack of potatoes. She grabbed Lillian by the wrist and flung her through the next open bulkhead, followed, and closed it behind her with a few quick taps on a panel Lillian hadn't even noticed.

"Got his disaster response priority wrong," she explained as she used her keycard to lock the heavy door.

"Kinda thin evidence for killing somebody." Lillian's voice was flat. She hoped she wasn't going into shock already.

"He's just winded. I shot him where the armour is thickest, just in case. Worst case scenario, broken rib."

The containment breach lights were on, but there was no alarm wailing. That was bad. There should have been a voice telling them what the problem was, which also wasn't happening. That was worse. Wheeler dragged her by the hand back down the hallway they'd taken, then sharply turned a corner and headed perpendicular to their original path. There could only be one explanation for such a diversion: the antimemeticist thought they were the target of the attack, and she was trying to occlude their location.

Fat lot of good that would do, with all the cameras in this damn place. The lower levels of Site-06 made Paramax look like Alcatraz.

As they passed an interrogation room, the door suddenly slid open and a pudgy-faced man clutching a binder appeared in the frame. "What's going on?"

Lillian took the binder from his hands and slammed it into his face. The binder was metal. It pulverized his nose. As he staggered back, screeching, blood pouring through the fingers clutching at his wound, Wheeler locked him in the office. She shot Lillian a questioning glance.

"Level two clearance badge. Shouldn't be down here."

Wheeler considered. "I think it was only the back half that's level three plus. Past the checkpoint."

"Oh." Lillian considered as well. "Probably still better that he's not roaming around. Safer in there."

Wheeler smiled for the first time. "With you out here, definitely. Know how to use a gun?"

She shook her head, then reached into her pants. There was no pocket. "No, but I've got something better. Something that doesn't set off metal detectors."

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

Wheeler disabled the next three suspected hostiles in ways which didn't allow Lillian to use her carry on luggage. One had either made the rookie mistake of becoming the spitting image of the man whose nose Lillian had just broken, or else was himself the real McCoy. Wheeler stuck him in an elevator and locked it down just to be safe. The next one was actually in the process of changing its face and clothes in the corridor when they crept up on it, so Wheeler took the shot. She blew out its kneecap, but then a whole load of its friends came rushing towards them and they had to lock the nearest bulkhead and detour. This presented them with a particularly ballsy //geistschreiber// masquerading as Wheeler herself. She shot that one in the head without blinking.

Lillian figured out the fourth and final one by what she felt was a brilliant process of deduction. They passed a locked lab with a panicked-looking janitor peering out the window at them, and they almost let it slide until Lillian noticed that the light over the keypad was red. Staff were given extra authority to lock doors during a security breach, but anything done outside their usual clearance level would produce an amber light instead.

That janitor apparently had researcher permissions.

Wheeler waited until they were out of his field of vision before shooting the window glass out, reaching in, and pulling the dazed impostor into the corridor.

Before he could react, Lillian stuck a thin piece of card in his face. "Cooperation," she said.

He stared at her.

She showed him the next card. His eyes flicked briefly from side to side. He wanted not to look, but had no lasting control now. "Abstract thought."

He blinked. "//Guernica.// You ever see it? They covered it up, you know, when we went to war in Iraq. Everyone is happy to countenance the horrors of armed conflict until we really, //really// want to prosecute one."

She showed him the next card, after selecting carefully. "Motivating forces."

He grunted. His eyes were narrowed. Right about now he was getting a killer migraine. "The only thing that keeps me getting up in the morning is Pop Tarts. I like them uncooked."

She smiled. She'd heard this progressive limitation of people's possible avenues of thought, MARSTON Verification Protocol, described as torture. It left your mind stuck in an increasingly constricted space until it was just you and the desired information. As methods of interrogation went, however, it was a lot less invasive than just beating the truth out of the target.

"Mission objectives."

His eyes filled with tears with the strain of trying to resist. "Keep casualties to a minimum. Extract only when ready. Don't break cover."

She pulled the last card. "Operative subject."

He sagged. "Capture the vessel."

"What vessel? Vessel for what?"

The man screamed.

"Who's the vessel?" she shouted to be heard.

Like she'd flicked a switch, he stopped screaming. "You," he said through clenched teeth. "You're the fucking vessel."

[[=]]
@@ @@
[[image http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/the-b-b-decommission/Asterisk43.png]]
@@ @@
[[/=]]

"What did he mean, you're the vessel?" They were running now, and Wheeler was shooting out every camera they came across. She had an extra magazine stashed in her belt that Lillian had never even suspected beneath that immaculately fitted suit.

"I don't know."

"Why did he scream when you asked him what goes inside?"

"Best guess? He was trapped in his own brain with antimemetic information. Whatever's in the vessel can't be properly conceived." She was beginning to think the survival training hadn't been a tremendous waste of time after all. Wheeler was obviously in tip-top shape, and it was good to be able to run, gun, and jaw at the same time.

"So, there's something terrible inside of you."

"Heard that one before," Lillian grimaced. "You gonna shoot me?"

Wheeler stopped them at the next corner. Lillian put a foot up against the wall as her partner prepared to swing her weapon out into the hall. "Keeping my options open."

Finally, urgently, as though realizing it was late to the party, a hollow screeching filled the halls. The solid red lights began to flash.

"Oh," said Wheeler.

"Uh," Lillian agreed.

It was the nuclear overload alarm.

