Wettle had done his research. He had learned that falling when limp was safer than falling when tense. This, he felt, qualified as humour.

Because while he'd been running away from a fire in his office back in 2002, he hadn't expected the perpendicular pile driver of security agents that took him down, so he'd probably struck the tiles in a relatively relaxed pose. This time, he was going to see it coming.

It was definitely going to hurt a whole lot more.

Next year, he thought, he would consider padding his pants.

If he remembered.

