Lillian didn't look up from the report she was writing. Her internal clock was precise down to the second. She pressed what she needed to press, she said what she needed to say -- in the context of Del Olmo's death this phrasing was a revolting irony, but she refused to linger on it -- and she did it without ever dipping below one hundred words per minute.

She didn't even know they'd done it right until McInnis called her on the radio for debriefing.

"Same time next year," she muttered, and kept tapping away at her tablet. What was there even to debrief?

2002 was over, again.

