++ 18 November
[[/=]]

----

"What was the point of it all?"

Ngo glanced down at him. "What do you mean?"

Harry shifted on the couch. "I don't remember it. Nobody remembers it."

"We're still talking about 5243-A? I wouldn't say //nobody// remembers it. And of course we got some of it recorded."

"Hardly anything. A whole goddamn year." He heard the bitterness in his voice, but couldn't bring himself to correct it. "Most of it's gone."

"You can read the parts that weren't," she pointed out. "They haven't been lost just because they didn't..."

"Because they didn't happen," he finished for her. "You were going to say they didn't happen."

She sighed. "It did happen. It was real."

"And now it isn't. So what? What did we get out of that?"

"We learned some vital information," she ventured.

"A whole year." He stared at the ceiling, seeing something else entirely. "We started to rebuild the entire world. We started new lives. And now it's gone."

"Is being able to read about it really that different from having the memories?"

He ignored her, which rather defeated the purpose of the session, but //who the fuck cares.// "It's like it happened to someone else, and all I have is the summary they thought was important. I didn't grow the way I... the way he... the way I would have, if I still remembered. It's not my experience, it's…" He clutched at the cushions in frustration. "It's just a story they're telling me. It's barely vicarious."

"Well," she offered, "it isn't like you've lost a year or anything. You still have your proper memories."

He looked up at her. "Is that what they are? My proper memories? Did this version of me," and he tapped his chest for an emphasis even he didn't really understand, "do those things, or the things I can't remember anymore? How do I know the memories I still have aren't just a lie I tell myself?"

"Harry," she smiled kindly. "That's all memories ever are."

